Lesson 4 Introduction

ANTH 102-W1

So, now you know what archaeology is, how to do it, and how archaeologists interpret their results in order to reconstruct the past. Now, it is time to consider the state of archaeology today. In this lesson, we will further explore the following: the goals of archaeology and the theoretical approaches archaeologists use to get from observed data to interpretation; the types of education and training necessary to be a professional archaeologist; the growing importance of public/community archaeology; and ethical issues related to archaeology.



In this lesson, we will focus on the following:

  • the methods that archaeologists use to analyze their data;
  • the theoretical frameworks in which archaeologists interpret the results of those analyses in order to reconstruct the past;
  • some basic models of cultural change;
  • archaeology today, including the concepts of public/community archaeology, working with descendant communities; and
  • the protection of cultural heritage (specifically archaeological resources) from looters and in areas of armed conflict.

Objectives

By the end of this lesson, you should be able to successfully:

  • Review methods and theory in archaeology (cultural ecology, ethnoarchaeology, experimental archaeology, general systems theory, processual and postprocessual archaeology).

  • Understand common archaeological units (time/space), such as component, phase, tradition, etc.

  • Understand common models for cultural change (for example, innovation and diffusion) and processes by which cultures change.

  • Categorize the practice of archaeology today (public archaeology, cultural resources management (CRM).

  • Describe some of the legal and ethical issues in archaeology (e.g., curation, conservation, looting, stewardship, colonial legacies).

  • Understand the educational/experience requirements for professional archaeologists.
